Architecture plan for issues #101-#107: external substrate measurement backends

Scope and guiding principle
- Keep ref_abr as a lightweight ABR scheduling, accounting, metrics, and replay toolkit.
- Do not copy or reimplement codec, decoder, transcoder, or renderer algorithms in this repository.
- Integrate CAGS, PyAV, and ffmpeg-python only through optional, thin adapter layers that emit normalized timing/quality/artifact records consumed by the existing substrate, scheduler, harness, and metrics code.

Module structure and file organization
- src/ref_abr/external_records.py or src/ref_abr/schema_extensions.py
  - Versioned external-measurement record dataclass/parsing helpers.
  - JSON/JSONL/YAML load and validation functions reusing ref_abr.schema/config conventions.
  - Canonical fields: generation_ms, transfer_ms, decode_ms, restore_ms, render_ms, encoded_bytes/size_bytes, visible_quality, dropped_frame, deadline_hit, artifact/provenance metadata.
- src/ref_abr/providers/__init__.py
  - Public provider exports and optional-backend discovery helpers.
- src/ref_abr/providers/base.py
  - ExternalSubstrateProvider protocol/base class.
  - Common mapping from validated external records to SubstrateValue and ComponentTiming.
  - Backend selection factory driven by config/provider_id while preserving existing parametric and empirical-table defaults.
- src/ref_abr/providers/cags.py
  - Optional adapter that assembles arguments for cags.encode/decode/pickup/render, invokes installed CAGS APIs, measures/collects output timings, compressed directory/.ply/.drc sizes, PSNR/LPIPS, and maps records to gaussian_base, gaussian_enhancement, tile, and reference_action candidates.
  - Raises clear optional-dependency errors if CAGS is absent.
- src/ref_abr/providers/pyav_decode.py
  - Optional provider using PyAV to read frame/container metadata and measure decode_ms and size_bytes.
  - Emits external-measurement records without implementing a decoder.
- src/ref_abr/providers/ffmpeg_ladder.py
  - Optional provider that scripts ffmpeg-python/ffmpeg for offline transcode, scale, and bitrate-ladder traces.
  - Emits encode/generation size and timing records without implementing an encoder.
- pyproject.toml
  - Keep default install small: click and PyYAML only.
  - Add extras: cags, video, render, test. Place PyAV/ffmpeg-python under video; CAGS and render libraries under cags/render only when appropriate.
- README.md / PRODUCT.md / usage docs
  - Document install extras, CAGS git install, backend selection config, expected trace formats, and licensing caveats.
- tests/
  - Unit tests for schema validation and mapping.
  - Mocked adapter tests for CAGS/PyAV/ffmpeg invocations.
  - Offline trace fixture end-to-end test through run_harness -> compute_metrics with deterministic outputs.

Shared types and contracts
- External measurement records are public, version-stamped contracts; incompatible schema versions fail fast.
- Provenance should include backend name/version, source path or content id, command/API arguments, timestamps where relevant, and artifact references/sizes.
- Provider outputs should normalize to existing SubstrateValue/ComponentTiming instead of introducing a parallel timing model.
- Candidate-kind mapping stays aligned with existing candidate constants: gaussian_base, gaussian_enhancement, tile, reference_action.
- Optional providers must be import-safe: importing ref_abr must not require CAGS, PyAV, ffmpeg-python, CUDA, or native renderer dependencies.

Issue dependency flow
- #101 defines the external-measurement trace schema and validation utilities. All later provider issues depend on this record contract.
- #102 adds the providers package, base provider interface, record-to-substrate mapping, and config-driven backend selection. CAGS/PyAV/ffmpeg adapters depend on this foundation.
- #103 implements the CAGS 3DGS codec/render adapter as an optional backend using #101 records and #102 provider mapping.
- #104 implements the PyAV decode-profiler provider as an optional video backend using #101/#102.
- #105 implements the ffmpeg-python transcode/ladder trace provider as an optional offline video backend using #101/#102.
- #106 adds optional dependency extras and docs after provider APIs settle, documenting each backend and keeping default dependencies minimal.
- #107 adds mocked functional tests and an offline trace end-to-end check after schema, base provider, adapters, and docs are in place.

Key design decisions
- Prefer trace-first operation: real codec/render/player tools generate measurements, while ref_abr validates, maps, schedules, and evaluates them.
- Never vendor third-party codec/render code; optional adapters should remain small and replaceable.
- Keep provider selection declarative in config so experiments can switch among parametric, empirical-table, and external backends without code changes.
- Use dependency injection and mocks in tests so CI does not need real CAGS, PyAV, ffmpeg, CUDA, or media assets.
- Preserve deterministic serialization for records and artifacts to support reproducible harness outputs and paper-output derivation.
- Treat filesystem artifacts as references in records; the core scheduling path should consume normalized metadata and timings, not binary blobs.
- Provide clear error messages for missing optional extras, including which extra to install and which config requested the backend.
